Amend the European stability pact
The European stability pact, which supports the euro by establishing constraints determining the size of the budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavyweights of the Union, has not managed to meet its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Moreover, it has used its political weight to cover up the early warning of its deficit, issued by the European Commission in accordance with the terms of the stability pact.
Today it is France that is playing the bad guy.
The number two of the Union, not very enthusiastic, has in turn unofficially declared its inability to meet its commitment to reduce its budget deficit, a year after the small Ireland received an official warning regarding its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the stability pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems greatly affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it, as well as the discussions aimed at amending it.
And rightly so: the pact is ill-conceived and its implementation is poorly done.
The limitation of the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and disregards the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Admitting this fact, the architects of the pact have worsened the situation by adopting two "poorly thought-out" solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in the event of a significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is practically impossible in practice.
Concerned that serious slowdowns could undermine the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit was equivalent to zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a two-year forward-looking budget demonstrating how the budgetary balance will be achieved in a timely manner.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable rate.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal contractionary policy.
The Commission, seeking to position itself as the pact's protector, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation of France is different.
In election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, notably of tax burden reduction.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it is not only a matter of political intelligence, but also economic intelligence, as long as budgetary expenditures are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges funded by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitely poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot meet its targets and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has become a master at defying the laws of the Union.
Political maneuvering will inevitably follow.
Economists and cynics are not particularly surprised.
The objective of the pact, to establish fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is entirely legitimate.
However, having lost control of their national monetary policies, members of the Union are left with only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The stability pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look very far.
Monetary policy is faced with the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the last ten years, monetary policy achieved real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it is enough to delegate this policy to a competent group, the central bank, granting it the necessary political independence and a clear, well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any deviation must be addressed in the future, it is up to him to use common sense.
This has proven to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Some, of course, fear losing out on democracy.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of spending and in terms of revenues.
Decisions concerning these issues cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management.
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budgetary balance to manage cycles of fluctuation.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure its effectiveness, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must be the subject of a consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulations, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
